Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the repercussions of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states face a particularly complex set of challenges.
Indeed, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already facing poverty, conflicts, corruption, and inadequate public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: a functioning state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, and health services to care for infected individuals.
The lack of resources by the state is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three fans for the entire country.
An effective response also requires confidence in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states enjoys little popular support.
In countries recovering from a conflict or experiencing endemic corruption, many people will be reluctant to support the government, even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work in order to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues in order to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states might avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the young population and geographic remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, we must note that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all experienced infection and mortality rates comparable to those of developed countries that were initially hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These will not only result from national lockdowns, but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have fallen, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are piling up.
Since fragile states rely heavily on imports for most of their food, there is increasing talk of "hunger" and even "famine."
We should now have understood that the problems of less developed countries are becoming, for the most part, global issues, whether in the form of mass migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the vulnerable populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will continue to worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must address.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim will be to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and who will address their broader and deeper issues.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the prudent use of data will be essential.
For example, it is widely proven that "targeted lockdowns" of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
Nevertheless, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades away.
We propose five recommendations.
First, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to provide regular small stipends (although for a limited period).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which used to grow rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
More generally, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local initiatives for the production of staple crops must be rapidly scaled up to a much larger extent.
Thirdly, once vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines in order to ensure a rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development, small businesses in less developed countries are often neglected and suffer the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need larger investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support fragile, highly indebted states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay about $40 billion to private and public creditors this year alone.
In order to prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debt not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Moreover, it is crucial that all fragile states receive emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic impacts — particularly countries that do not usually have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all the fragile states of the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we will be able to mitigate the worst consequences of the pandemic.
If there is indeed a lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
